{"title_page": "Andrew Clarke (British Army officer, born 1824)", "text_new": "{{other people|Andrew Clarke}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox Governor\n| honorific-prefix = [[Lieutenant-General (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]]\n| name          = Sir Andrew Clarke\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCMG|CB|CIE}}\n| image         =Sir Andrew Clarke (1873) by G R Lambert.jpg\n| order         = Colonel Commandant, Royal Engineers\n| term_start    =1901\n| term_end      =1902\n| predecessor   = General Charles Fanshawe\n| successor     =[[Charles Brisbane Ewart|Lieutenant-General Charles B. Ewart]]\n| order1        = [[Chief Royal Engineer|Inspector-General of Fortifications and Director of Work]]\n| term_start1   =1882\n| term_end1     =1886\n| predecessor1  = Thomas Gallwey\n| successor1    =[[Lothian Nicholson]]\n| order2        =9th [[Governor of Straits Settlements]]\n| term_start2   =4 November 1873\n| term_end2     =8 May 1875\n| monarch2      = [[Queen Victoria]]\n| 1blankname2   = [[Chief Secretary for Administration|Colonial Secretary]]\n| 1namedata2    = [[James W. W. Birch]]<br>[[Thomas Braddell]]\n| predecessor2  = Sir [[Harry Ord]]\n| successor2    = Sir [[William Jervois]]\n| order3        = [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]]<br>[[Electoral district of South Melbourne|(Member for South Melbourne)]]\n| term_start3   =November 1856\n| term_end3     =August 1858\n| predecessor3  = '''New district'''\n| successor3    =[[Robert Stirling Hore Anderson|Robert Anderson]]\n| order4        = [[Victorian Legislative Council]]<br>(Nominated member)\n| term_start4   =29 August 1853\n| term_end4     =March 1856\n| predecessor4  = '''New seat'''\n| successor4    ='''Original Council abolished'''\n| order5        =[[Surveyor General of Victoria]]\n| term_start5   =May 1853\n| term_end5     =March 1857\n| predecessor5  = [[Robert Hoddle]]\n| successor5    = [[George Horne (politician)|George Horne]]\n| birth_date    ={{birth date|1824|7|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place   =[[Southsea]], [[Hampshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date    ={{death date and age|1902|3|29|1824|7|27|df=y}}\n| death_place   =[[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[Somerset]]\n| spouse        =Lady Frances Jackson\n| religion      =[[Christianity|Christian]]\n| constituency  =\n| party         =\n| signature =\n}}\n[[Lieutenant-General (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]] '''Sir Andrew Clarke,''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|GCMG|CB|CIE}} (27 July 1824 \u2013 29 March 1902) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] soldier and governor, as well as a surveyor and politician in [[Australia]].<ref name=adb>Betty Malone, '[http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/clarke-sir-andrew-3219  Clarke, Sir Andrew (1824\u20131902)]', ''[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]'', Vol.3, [[Melbourne University Press|MUP]], 1969, pp 409\u2013411.</ref>\n\n==Background and education==\nBorn in [[Southsea]], [[Hampshire]], Clarke was the eldest of the four sons of [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] Sir [[Andrew Clarke (British Army officer, born 1793)|Andrew Clarke]], the [[Governor of Western Australia]]<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Clarke, Sir Andrew|volume=6|page=443}}</ref> (1793\u20131847). Clarke's early years were spent in India with his parents. He was later brought up by his paternal grandfather and two uncles, one of whom was the father of [[Marcus Clarke]], at the family home of Belmont, near [[Lifford]], Ireland. He was educated at [[The King's School, Canterbury]], and at [[Portora Royal School]] at [[Enniskillen]], [[Ireland]]. At 16 he entered the [[Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]], where one of his teachers was [[Michael Faraday]].<ref name=adb/>\n\n==Career==\nGraduating in 1844, Clarke was commissioned a 2nd Lieutenant in the [[Royal Engineers]] and after a year of further study at [[Chatham, Medway|Chatham]] was sent to [[Fermoy]] in Ireland. In 1846 he was nominated to the [[Oregon boundary dispute|Oregon Boundary Commission]]; his father, who was then governor of [[Western Australia]], urged him instead to come to Australia with the hope of later gaining a professional post with him. As a lieutenant in command of a detachment of Royal Engineers, Clarke sailed with the new lieutenant-governor, [[William Denison|Sir William Denison]], aboard the ''Windermere'' and arrived at [[Hobart]] on 26 January 1847. His father's death the following next month left Clarke with little reason to remain in Australia but he continued to superintend convict labour and to survey the area around Hobart and design wharf accommodation and became friends with William Denison.<ref name=adb/>\n\nClarke's next tour of duty was in [[New Zealand]] with governor [[George Grey|Sir George Grey]], from September 1848. He and his detachment worked mainly on road building, and Clarke discovered his gift for dealing with native peoples when he was sent on a peace-making mission to the [[Bay of Islands]].<ref name=adb/>\n\nIn 1849 Clarke returned to Hobart to become private secretary to William Denison, [[Governor]] of [[Tasmania]] and [[New South Wales]], and was also an official nominee in the [[Tasmanian Legislative Council]] in 1851\u201353 and controller of the [[mounted police]].<ref name=adb/>\n\nIn March 1853 Clarke was asked to replace [[Robert Hoddle]] as [[Surveyor General of Victoria]] and arrived at [[Melbourne]] in May. His hard work and energy resulted in more land being sold in the next 18 months than in the years since 1836. He also established the Roads Boards that preceded the introduction of local government and was responsible for much of the planning of Victoria's first railways. His proposals for a government-controlled railway system were examined by a select committee and were made law in 1857. Additionally, he set up the first electric telegraph from Melbourne to [[Williamstown, Victoria]] and was able to report in November 1857 that the service had reached the borders of New South Wales and [[South Australia]].<ref name=adb/> In 1855 he was elected the inaugural president of the [[Philosophical Institute of Victoria]].<ref>[http://www.burkeandwills.net.au/Royal_Society/Philosophical_Institute_of_Victoria.htm Office Bearers of the Philosophical Institute of Victoria  Burke & Wills Web : the digital research archive]</ref>\n\nClarke entered the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] in August 1853 as an official representative, where he was active in the drafting of the new constitution. He was also responsible for the drafting and successful inauguration of the Municipal Institutions Act in December 1854, which provided for local government based on the English model in Melbourne's growing suburbs, on the goldfields, and in the country.<ref name=adb/>\n\nAt the 1856 elections, Clarke mounted a successful campaign against [[David Blair (encyclopedist)|David Blair]] for the [[Electoral district of South Melbourne|South Melbourne]] seat in the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]], which he held until he left the colony. He joined the first cabinet under [[William Haines (Australian politician)|William Haines]], as Surveyor-General and Commissioner for Lands.<ref name=adb/>\n\nIn March 1858 Clarke was appointed permanent head of the Lands and Surveys Department and decided to return to England. In London, he tried and failed to secure the governorship of [[Queensland]] and spent some months on barrack duty at [[Colchester]].<ref name=adb/>\n\nFrom 1859 to 1864 Clarke served in the African colony of the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]] and in England, where he was Director of Works at the [[Admiralty]] from 1864\u20131873.<ref name=adb/> During this period he co-authored a report on the Suez Canal with [[George Henry Richards]], Hydrographer to the Admiralty<ref>{{cite journal|first1=George Henry|last1=Richards|first2=Andrew|last2=Clarke|title=Report on the Suez Canal|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Geographical Society of London|date=1869|volume=14|issue=3|pages=259\u2013273|jstor=1799058|doi=10.2307/1799058}}</ref>\n\n===Governor of the Straits Settlements===\n[[File:Bust of Sir Andrew Clarke, Victoria Concert Hall, Singapore - 20141101-01.JPG|thumb|upright|A bust of Clarke in [[Victoria Theatre and Concert Hall|Victoria Concert Hall]], Singapore]]\n\nSir Andrew Clarke served as the Governor of Singapore and the [[Governor of the Straits Settlements]] from 4 November 1873 until 8 May 1875. Clarke played a key role in positioning Singapore as the main port for the [[British Malaya|Malay]] states of [[Perak]], [[Selangor]] and [[Sungei Ujong]].\n\nDue to his contributions, [[Singapore]]'s [[Clarke Quay]] was named after him. Clarke Street, located next to Clarke Quay, was officially named in 1896 and was originally two streets known simply as East Street and West Street in north Kampong Malacca. Today it is a pedestrian mall and a popular nightspot.\n\n====Pangkor Treaty====\n{{See also|Pangkor Treaty of 1874}}\nAs [[Governor of the Straits Settlements]], Clarke was famous for signing the [[Treaty of Pangkor]] in 1874, which established indirect British rule over the [[Malay States]]. In that same year, Clarke successfully enforced a check on the abuse of [[coolie]]s with support of the prominent Chinese leaders and European merchants. Clarke achieved fame through his negotiations in regard to [[Sungai Ujong|Sungei Ujong]] in [[British Malaya|Malaya]], sorting out the differences between different leaders in [[Negeri Sembilan]].\n\nClarke was blamed for the death of the first British [[Resident (title)|resident]] in [[Perak]], [[James Wheeler Woodford Birch]], due to his ignorance of a complaint, when [[Abdullah Muhammad Shah II of Perak|Sultan Abdullah of Perak]] wrote a letter to inform him about Birch's rudeness against the [[Malay states|Malay]] rulers, because at that time he was about to retire and did not want that problem to destroy his reputation as one of the most successful colonial administrators.\n\n====Klang War====\n{{See also|Klang War}}\nClarke was instrumental in determining the outcome of the Klang War which took place from 1867 to 1874 as well as placing [[Selangor]] under British protection.\n\nThe [[Straits Settlements]] were becoming increasingly dependent on the economy of Selangor. Selangor through the 19th and the 20th was one of the world's major tin producers. Since Selangor's security affected tin trade, the British felt it needed to have a say in Selangor politics. The British saw Tengku Kudin as a ticket to reach out to Selangor's royal court. Therefore, the [[Straits Settlements]] led by Clarke implicitly supported Tengku Kudin in the war.\n\nThroughout the war, Tengku Kudin brought in soldiers from [[Kedah]] and [[Pahang]] along with mercenaries and [[Europe]]an officers from the [[Straits Settlements]]. The end result was a victory for Tengku Kudin.\n\nWhile the British through Clarke was on Tengku Kudin's side, the post-war situation had weakened Tengku Kudin's power base due to the Selangor royal family's suspicion of Tengku Kudin and the British. Therefore, Andrew Clarke was forced to freeze the plan to reach out to the royal family through Tengku Kudin.\n\nIn November 1873 however, a ship from Penang was attacked by pirates near [[Kuala Langat]], [[Selangor]]. After a number of piracy attacks took place in Selangor, Andrew Clarke assigned [[Frank Swettenham]] as a live-in advisor to [[Sultan Abdul Samad]] in August 1874. Sultan Abdul Samad accepted [[James Guthrie Davidson]], a lawyer from [[Singapore]], as the first [[British Resident]] of Selangor in 1875. In October the same year, Sultan Abdul Samad sent a letter to Andrew Clarke requesting for Selangor to be placed under the British [[protectorate]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Perisytiharan Pentadbiran Inggeris di Selangor |url=http://www.arkib.gov.my/hids/readarticle.php?article_id=3124 |date=3 December 2008 |publisher=National Archives of Malaysia |accessdate=29 June 2009 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"andaya\">{{Cite book | author= Andaya, B.W. | title = A History of Malaysia | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | year = 1984 | isbn = 978-0-312-38121-9 | postscript= <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n===Further service===\n[[File:Sir Andrew Clarke WDL11454.png|thumb|Sir Andrew Clarke during the Second Anglo-Afghan War]]\nFrom 1875 to 1880 Clarke was on the council of the [[Governor-General of India|Viceroy of India]]. He was Commandant of the [[Royal School of Military Engineering]] at Chatham from 1881\u20131882, and finally was Inspector-General of Fortifications in England from 1882 to 1886.\n\nAfter Clarke's retirement from the army, he unsuccessfully contested [[Chatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Chatham]] for the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]] in 1886 and 1892 as a follower of [[William Ewart Gladstone]] and [[Home Rule]]. Clarke retained an interest in the Australian colonies, and briefly acted as [[Agent-General#List of Agents-General for Victoria|Agent-General for Victoria]] in 1886, 1891, and 1893, before being appointed agent-general in 1899, which post he held until his death.\n\nClarke also served as a director of [[Palmers Shipbuilding and Iron Company]], the [[Colonial Mutual|Colonial Life Assurance Society]], the Delhi-Umbala Railway Co. and the [[North Borneo Chartered Company|British North Borneo Company]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Parkinson |first=C. Northcote |date=1960 |title=British Intervention in Malaya 1867-1877 |location=Singapore |publisher=University of Malaya Press |page=208}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1901 he was appointed [[Colonel commandant|Colonel Commandant]] of the Royal Engineers.<ref>{{London Gazette | issue=27399 | date=21 January 1902 |page=453}}</ref>\n\nClarke died at his house in [[Portland Place]], London, on 29 March 1902. He was predeceased by his wife, Mary Margaret MacKillop, whom he had married on 17 September 1867, and he was survived by their only child, Elinor Mary de Winton.<ref name=adb/>\n\n==Honours==\n* Appointed Companion of the [[Order of the Bath]] (CB), 1869.\n* Knight Commander of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG), 1873.\n* Companion of the [[Order of the Indian Empire]] (CIE), 1877.\n* Knight Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George (GCMG), 1885.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite DNB12|wstitle=Clarke, Andrew|first=Robert Hamilton|last=Vetch}}\n*{{cite book | last = Vetch | first = Robert Hamilton | authorlink = | title = Life of Lieut-General the Hon. Sir Andrew Clarke | publisher = E. P. Dutton and Company | year = 1905 | location = Plymouth | pages = | url =https://archive.org/details/lifelieutgenera01vetcgoog| doi = | id = | isbn = }}\n*{{Dictionary of Australian Biography|First=Andrew|Last=Clarke|shortlink=0-dict-biogCl-Cu.html#clarke1|accessdate=2016-11-02}}\n{{Commons category|Andrew Clarke (British Army officer)}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = [[Surveyor General of Victoria]]\n | years  = May 1853 \u2013 March 1857\n | before = [[Robert Hoddle]]\n | after  = [[George Horne (Australian politician)|George Horne]]\n}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-lc}}\n{{s-new | seat }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = Nominated member\n | years = 29 August 1853 \u2013 March 1856}}\n{{s-non | reason = Original Council<br>abolished}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-la}}\n{{s-new| district}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of South Melbourne|South Melbourne]]|years=November 1856 \u2013 August 1858}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Anderson (Australian politician)|Robert Anderson]]}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Governor of Straits Settlements]] | before=[[Harry Ord|Sir Harry Ord]] | after= [[William Jervois|Sir William Jervois]] | years=4 November 1874 \u2013 8 May 1875}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Thomas Lionel John Gallwey|Thomas Gallwey]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Chief Royal Engineer|Inspector-General of Fortifications <br/>and Director of Work]]\n       | years  = 1882\u20131886 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Lothian Nicholson]] }}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Charles Fanshawe|General Charles Fanshawe]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Colonel Commandant Royal Engineers|Colonel Commandant, Royal Engineers]]\n       | years  = 1901\u20131902 }}\n{{s-aft| after  =  [[Charles Brisbane Ewart|Lieutenant-General Charles B. Ewart]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Governors of Singapore}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clarke, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1824 births]]\n[[Category:1902 deaths]]\n[[Category:Royal Engineers officers]]\n[[Category:British Army generals]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the New Zealand Wars]]\n[[Category:Governors of the Straits Settlements]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Indian Empire]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:People educated at Portora Royal School]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Canterbury]]\n[[Category:People from Southsea]]\n[[Category:Administrators in British Malaya]]\n[[Category:Surveyors General of Victoria]]\n[[Category:Agents-General for Victoria]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian public servants]]\n[[Category:Administrators in British Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Andrew Clarke}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox Governor\n| honorific-prefix = [[Lieutenant-General (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]]\n| name          = Sir Andrew Clarke\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCMG|CB|CIE}}\n| image         =Sir Andrew Clarke (1873) by G R Lambert.jpg\n| order         = Colonel Commandant, Royal Engineers\n| term_start    =1901\n| term_end      =1902\n| predecessor   = General Charles Fanshawe\n| successor     =[[Charles Brisbane Ewart|Lieutenant-General Charles B. Ewart]]\n| order1        = [[Chief Royal Engineer|Inspector-General of Fortifications and Director of Work]]\n| term_start1   =1882\n| term_end1     =1886\n| predecessor1  = Thomas Gallwey\n| successor1    =[[Lothian Nicholson]]\n| order2        =9th [[Governor of Straits Settlements]]\n| term_start2   =4 November 1873\n| term_end2     =8 May 1875\n| monarch2      = [[Queen Victoria]]\n| 1blankname2   = [[Chief Secretary for Administration|Colonial Secretary]]\n| 1namedata2    = [[James W. W. Birch]]<br>[[Thomas Braddell]]\n| predecessor2  = Sir [[Harry Ord]]\n| successor2    = Sir [[William Jervois]]\n| order3        = [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]]<br>[[Electoral district of South Melbourne|(Member for South Melbourne)]]\n| term_start3   =November 1856\n| term_end3     =August 1858\n| predecessor3  = '''New district'''\n| successor3    =[[Robert Stirling Hore Anderson|Robert Anderson]]\n| order4        = [[Victorian Legislative Council]]<br>(Nominated member)\n| term_start4   =29 August 1853\n| term_end4     =March 1856\n| predecessor4  = '''New seat'''\n| successor4    ='''Original Council abolished'''\n| order5        =[[Surveyor General of Victoria]]\n| term_start5   =May 1853\n| term_end5     =March 1857\n| predecessor5  = [[Robert Hoddle]]\n| successor5    = [[George Horne (politician)|George Horne]]\n| birth_date    ={{birth date|1824|7|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place   =[[Southsea]], [[Hampshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date    ={{death date and age|1902|3|29|1824|7|27|df=y}}\n| death_place   =[[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[Somerset]]\n| spouse        =Lady Frances Jackson\n| religion      =[[Christianity|Christian]]\n| constituency  =\n| party         =\n| signature =\n}}\n[[Lieutenant-General (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]] '''Sir Andrew Clarke,''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|GCMG|CB|CIE}} (27 July 1824 \u2013 29 March 1902) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] soldier and governor, as well as a surveyor and politician in [[Australia]].<ref name=adb>Betty Malone, '[http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/clarke-sir-andrew-3219  Clarke, Sir Andrew (1824\u20131902)]', ''[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]'', Vol.3, [[Melbourne University Press|MUP]], 1969, pp 409\u2013411.</ref>\n\n==Background and education==\nBorn in [[Southsea]], [[Hampshire]], Clarke was the eldest of the four sons of [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] Sir [[Andrew Clarke (governor)|Andrew Clarke]], the [[Governor of Western Australia]]<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Clarke, Sir Andrew|volume=6|page=443}}</ref> (1793\u20131847). Clarke's early years were spent in India with his parents. He was later brought up by his paternal grandfather and two uncles, one of whom was the father of [[Marcus Clarke]], at the family home of Belmont, near [[Lifford]], Ireland. He was educated at [[The King's School, Canterbury]], and at [[Portora Royal School]] at [[Enniskillen]], [[Ireland]]. At 16 he entered the [[Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]], where one of his teachers was [[Michael Faraday]].<ref name=adb/>\n\n==Career==\nGraduating in 1844, Clarke was commissioned a 2nd Lieutenant in the [[Royal Engineers]] and after a year of further study at [[Chatham, Medway|Chatham]] was sent to [[Fermoy]] in Ireland. In 1846 he was nominated to the [[Oregon boundary dispute|Oregon Boundary Commission]]; his father, who was then governor of [[Western Australia]], urged him instead to come to Australia with the hope of later gaining a professional post with him. As a lieutenant in command of a detachment of Royal Engineers, Clarke sailed with the new lieutenant-governor, [[William Denison|Sir William Denison]], aboard the ''Windermere'' and arrived at [[Hobart]] on 26 January 1847. His father's death the following next month left Clarke with little reason to remain in Australia but he continued to superintend convict labour and to survey the area around Hobart and design wharf accommodation and became friends with William Denison.<ref name=adb/>\n\nClarke's next tour of duty was in [[New Zealand]] with governor [[George Grey|Sir George Grey]], from September 1848. He and his detachment worked mainly on road building, and Clarke discovered his gift for dealing with native peoples when he was sent on a peace-making mission to the [[Bay of Islands]].<ref name=adb/>\n\nIn 1849 Clarke returned to Hobart to become private secretary to William Denison, [[Governor]] of [[Tasmania]] and [[New South Wales]], and was also an official nominee in the [[Tasmanian Legislative Council]] in 1851\u201353 and controller of the [[mounted police]].<ref name=adb/>\n\nIn March 1853 Clarke was asked to replace [[Robert Hoddle]] as [[Surveyor General of Victoria]] and arrived at [[Melbourne]] in May. His hard work and energy resulted in more land being sold in the next 18 months than in the years since 1836. He also established the Roads Boards that preceded the introduction of local government and was responsible for much of the planning of Victoria's first railways. His proposals for a government-controlled railway system were examined by a select committee and were made law in 1857. Additionally, he set up the first electric telegraph from Melbourne to [[Williamstown, Victoria]] and was able to report in November 1857 that the service had reached the borders of New South Wales and [[South Australia]].<ref name=adb/> In 1855 he was elected the inaugural president of the [[Philosophical Institute of Victoria]].<ref>[http://www.burkeandwills.net.au/Royal_Society/Philosophical_Institute_of_Victoria.htm Office Bearers of the Philosophical Institute of Victoria  Burke & Wills Web : the digital research archive]</ref>\n\nClarke entered the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] in August 1853 as an official representative, where he was active in the drafting of the new constitution. He was also responsible for the drafting and successful inauguration of the Municipal Institutions Act in December 1854, which provided for local government based on the English model in Melbourne's growing suburbs, on the goldfields, and in the country.<ref name=adb/>\n\nAt the 1856 elections, Clarke mounted a successful campaign against [[David Blair (encyclopedist)|David Blair]] for the [[Electoral district of South Melbourne|South Melbourne]] seat in the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]], which he held until he left the colony. He joined the first cabinet under [[William Haines (Australian politician)|William Haines]], as Surveyor-General and Commissioner for Lands.<ref name=adb/>\n\nIn March 1858 Clarke was appointed permanent head of the Lands and Surveys Department and decided to return to England. In London, he tried and failed to secure the governorship of [[Queensland]] and spent some months on barrack duty at [[Colchester]].<ref name=adb/>\n\nFrom 1859 to 1864 Clarke served in the African colony of the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]] and in England, where he was Director of Works at the [[Admiralty]] from 1864\u20131873.<ref name=adb/> During this period he co-authored a report on the Suez Canal with [[George Henry Richards]], Hydrographer to the Admiralty<ref>{{cite journal|first1=George Henry|last1=Richards|first2=Andrew|last2=Clarke|title=Report on the Suez Canal|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Geographical Society of London|date=1869|volume=14|issue=3|pages=259\u2013273|jstor=1799058|doi=10.2307/1799058}}</ref>\n\n===Governor of the Straits Settlements===\n[[File:Bust of Sir Andrew Clarke, Victoria Concert Hall, Singapore - 20141101-01.JPG|thumb|upright|A bust of Clarke in [[Victoria Theatre and Concert Hall|Victoria Concert Hall]], Singapore]]\n\nSir Andrew Clarke served as the Governor of Singapore and the [[Governor of the Straits Settlements]] from 4 November 1873 until 8 May 1875. Clarke played a key role in positioning Singapore as the main port for the [[British Malaya|Malay]] states of [[Perak]], [[Selangor]] and [[Sungei Ujong]].\n\nDue to his contributions, [[Singapore]]'s [[Clarke Quay]] was named after him. Clarke Street, located next to Clarke Quay, was officially named in 1896 and was originally two streets known simply as East Street and West Street in north Kampong Malacca. Today it is a pedestrian mall and a popular nightspot.\n\n====Pangkor Treaty====\n{{See also|Pangkor Treaty of 1874}}\nAs [[Governor of the Straits Settlements]], Clarke was famous for signing the [[Treaty of Pangkor]] in 1874, which established indirect British rule over the [[Malay States]]. In that same year, Clarke successfully enforced a check on the abuse of [[coolie]]s with support of the prominent Chinese leaders and European merchants. Clarke achieved fame through his negotiations in regard to [[Sungai Ujong|Sungei Ujong]] in [[British Malaya|Malaya]], sorting out the differences between different leaders in [[Negeri Sembilan]].\n\nClarke was blamed for the death of the first British [[Resident (title)|resident]] in [[Perak]], [[James Wheeler Woodford Birch]], due to his ignorance of a complaint, when [[Abdullah Muhammad Shah II of Perak|Sultan Abdullah of Perak]] wrote a letter to inform him about Birch's rudeness against the [[Malay states|Malay]] rulers, because at that time he was about to retire and did not want that problem to destroy his reputation as one of the most successful colonial administrators.\n\n====Klang War====\n{{See also|Klang War}}\nClarke was instrumental in determining the outcome of the Klang War which took place from 1867 to 1874 as well as placing [[Selangor]] under British protection.\n\nThe [[Straits Settlements]] were becoming increasingly dependent on the economy of Selangor. Selangor through the 19th and the 20th was one of the world's major tin producers. Since Selangor's security affected tin trade, the British felt it needed to have a say in Selangor politics. The British saw Tengku Kudin as a ticket to reach out to Selangor's royal court. Therefore, the [[Straits Settlements]] led by Clarke implicitly supported Tengku Kudin in the war.\n\nThroughout the war, Tengku Kudin brought in soldiers from [[Kedah]] and [[Pahang]] along with mercenaries and [[Europe]]an officers from the [[Straits Settlements]]. The end result was a victory for Tengku Kudin.\n\nWhile the British through Clarke was on Tengku Kudin's side, the post-war situation had weakened Tengku Kudin's power base due to the Selangor royal family's suspicion of Tengku Kudin and the British. Therefore, Andrew Clarke was forced to freeze the plan to reach out to the royal family through Tengku Kudin.\n\nIn November 1873 however, a ship from Penang was attacked by pirates near [[Kuala Langat]], [[Selangor]]. After a number of piracy attacks took place in Selangor, Andrew Clarke assigned [[Frank Swettenham]] as a live-in advisor to [[Sultan Abdul Samad]] in August 1874. Sultan Abdul Samad accepted [[James Guthrie Davidson]], a lawyer from [[Singapore]], as the first [[British Resident]] of Selangor in 1875. In October the same year, Sultan Abdul Samad sent a letter to Andrew Clarke requesting for Selangor to be placed under the British [[protectorate]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Perisytiharan Pentadbiran Inggeris di Selangor |url=http://www.arkib.gov.my/hids/readarticle.php?article_id=3124 |date=3 December 2008 |publisher=National Archives of Malaysia |accessdate=29 June 2009 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"andaya\">{{Cite book | author= Andaya, B.W. | title = A History of Malaysia | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | year = 1984 | isbn = 978-0-312-38121-9 | postscript= <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n===Further service===\n[[File:Sir Andrew Clarke WDL11454.png|thumb|Sir Andrew Clarke during the Second Anglo-Afghan War]]\nFrom 1875 to 1880 Clarke was on the council of the [[Governor-General of India|Viceroy of India]]. He was Commandant of the [[Royal School of Military Engineering]] at Chatham from 1881\u20131882, and finally was Inspector-General of Fortifications in England from 1882 to 1886.\n\nAfter Clarke's retirement from the army, he unsuccessfully contested [[Chatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Chatham]] for the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]] in 1886 and 1892 as a follower of [[William Ewart Gladstone]] and [[Home Rule]]. Clarke retained an interest in the Australian colonies, and briefly acted as [[Agent-General#List of Agents-General for Victoria|Agent-General for Victoria]] in 1886, 1891, and 1893, before being appointed agent-general in 1899, which post he held until his death.\n\nClarke also served as a director of [[Palmers Shipbuilding and Iron Company]], the [[Colonial Mutual|Colonial Life Assurance Society]], the Delhi-Umbala Railway Co. and the [[North Borneo Chartered Company|British North Borneo Company]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Parkinson |first=C. Northcote |date=1960 |title=British Intervention in Malaya 1867-1877 |location=Singapore |publisher=University of Malaya Press |page=208}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1901 he was appointed [[Colonel commandant|Colonel Commandant]] of the Royal Engineers.<ref>{{London Gazette | issue=27399 | date=21 January 1902 |page=453}}</ref>\n\nClarke died at his house in [[Portland Place]], London, on 29 March 1902. He was predeceased by his wife, Mary Margaret MacKillop, whom he had married on 17 September 1867, and he was survived by their only child, Elinor Mary de Winton.<ref name=adb/>\n\n==Honours==\n* Appointed Companion of the [[Order of the Bath]] (CB), 1869.\n* Knight Commander of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG), 1873.\n* Companion of the [[Order of the Indian Empire]] (CIE), 1877.\n* Knight Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George (GCMG), 1885.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite DNB12|wstitle=Clarke, Andrew|first=Robert Hamilton|last=Vetch}}\n*{{cite book | last = Vetch | first = Robert Hamilton | authorlink = | title = Life of Lieut-General the Hon. Sir Andrew Clarke | publisher = E. P. Dutton and Company | year = 1905 | location = Plymouth | pages = | url =https://archive.org/details/lifelieutgenera01vetcgoog| doi = | id = | isbn = }}\n*{{Dictionary of Australian Biography|First=Andrew|Last=Clarke|shortlink=0-dict-biogCl-Cu.html#clarke1|accessdate=2016-11-02}}\n{{Commons category|Andrew Clarke (British Army officer)}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = [[Surveyor General of Victoria]]\n | years  = May 1853 \u2013 March 1857\n | before = [[Robert Hoddle]]\n | after  = [[George Horne (Australian politician)|George Horne]]\n}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-lc}}\n{{s-new | seat }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = Nominated member\n | years = 29 August 1853 \u2013 March 1856}}\n{{s-non | reason = Original Council<br>abolished}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-la}}\n{{s-new| district}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of South Melbourne|South Melbourne]]|years=November 1856 \u2013 August 1858}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Anderson (Australian politician)|Robert Anderson]]}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Governor of Straits Settlements]] | before=[[Harry Ord|Sir Harry Ord]] | after= [[William Jervois|Sir William Jervois]] | years=4 November 1874 \u2013 8 May 1875}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Thomas Lionel John Gallwey|Thomas Gallwey]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Chief Royal Engineer|Inspector-General of Fortifications <br/>and Director of Work]]\n       | years  = 1882\u20131886 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Lothian Nicholson]] }}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Charles Fanshawe|General Charles Fanshawe]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Colonel Commandant Royal Engineers|Colonel Commandant, Royal Engineers]]\n       | years  = 1901\u20131902 }}\n{{s-aft| after  =  [[Charles Brisbane Ewart|Lieutenant-General Charles B. Ewart]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Governors of Singapore}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clarke, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1824 births]]\n[[Category:1902 deaths]]\n[[Category:Royal Engineers officers]]\n[[Category:British Army generals]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the New Zealand Wars]]\n[[Category:Governors of the Straits Settlements]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Indian Empire]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of S