\u201360 kg]]\n|{{n/a|Bye}}\n|{{flagIOC2athlete|E Ahangarian|IRI|2018 Asian Games}}<br>'''L''' 0\u20132\n|colspan=4|Did not advance\n|}\n<small>'''Key''': * TV \u2013 Technical victory.</small>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Nations at the 2018 Asian Games}}\n\n[[Category:Nations at the 2018 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Yemen at the Asian Games|2018]]\n[[Category:2018 in Yemeni sport|Asian Games]]\n", "name_user": "Jonesey95", "label": "safe", "comment": "FixLintererrors usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yemen_at_the_2018_Asian_Games"}
{"title_page": "Cane Corso", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox Dogbreed\n<!-- Put article text AFTER this infobox markup. See: -->\n<!-- Wikipedia:WikiProject Dog breeds/Templates for more info.-->\n| name = Cane Corso\n| image = CaneCorso (23).jpg\n| image_caption =\n| altname = {{flatlist|\n* Cane Corso Italiano\n* Italian Corso Dog\n* Italian Mastiff\n}}\n\n| country = [[Italy]]\n| weight = \n| maleweight = {{convert|45\u201350|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"FCI\">{{cite web |title=FCI Standard 343 |url=http://www.fci.be/Nomenclature/Standards/343g02-en.pdf |accessdate=17 October 2014 |publisher=FCI}}</ref>\n| femaleweight = {{convert|40|\u2013|45|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"FCI\" />\n| height = \n| maleheight = {{convert|62\u201370|cm|in|abbr=on}}\n| femaleheight = {{convert|58\u201366 |cm|in|abbr=on}}\n| ckcgroup = Group 3, Working\n| ckcmisc = true Dog\n| ckcstd = ?\n| fcigroup = 2\n| fcisection = 2.1 Molossian: Mastiff type\n| fcinum = 343\n| fcistd = http://www.fci.be/Nomenclature/Standards/343g02-en.pdf\n| akcgroup  = Working\n| akcstd = http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/cane-corso/\n| akcfss =\n| ukcgroup = Guardian Dog Group\n| ukcstd = https://www.ukcdogs.com/cane-corso-italiano\n}}<!-- End Infobox -->\n\nThe '''Cane Corso''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8ka\u02d0ne \u02c8k\u0254rso|pron}}) is a large [[dog breed]] of [[Southern Italy|Southern Italian]] origins that is used for [[Attack_dog|personal protection]], [[Tracking_(dog)|tracking]], [[police dog|law enforcement]], and as a [[guard dog]].<ref name=UKC>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukcdogs.com/cane-corso-italiano|title=Breed Standards : Cane Corso Italiano - United Kennel Club (UKC)|website=www.ukcdogs.com|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe Cane Corso is a large Italian [[Molosser]], which is closely related to the [[Neapolitan Mastiff]]. In name and form the Cane Corso predates its cousin the Neapolitan Mastiff. It is well muscled<ref name=\"Get to Know the Cane Corso\">[http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/cane-corso/#standard \"Get to Know the Cane Corso\"], 'The American Kennel Club', Retrieved 20 May 2014</ref> and less bulky than most other Mastiff breeds. The breed is known as a true and quite possibly the last of the [[coursing]] Mastiffs. The official [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Cynologique Internationale]] (FCI) standard expects ideal dogs to stand {{convert|58|-|70|cm|in|abbr=on}} at the [[withers]], with females in the lower range  ({{convert|58|-|66|cm|in|abbr=on}}) and males in the higher ({{convert|62|-|70|cm|in|abbr=on}}). Weight should be in keeping with the size and stature of these dogs, ranging from {{convert|45\u201350|kg|lb}} for males and from {{convert|40|\u2013|45|kg|lb}} for females.<ref name=\"FCI\"/>\n\nThe head of the Cane Corso is arguably its most important feature. It is large and imposing.  The forehead should be flat and convergent to the muzzle. The muzzle is flat, rectangular (when viewed from above), and generally as wide as it is long; approximately 33% the total length of the skull (a ratio of 2:1). The eyes are almond in shape, set straight and when viewed from the front, set slightly above the line of the muzzle. Darker eyes are preferred, however, the color of the eyes tends to emulate the shade of brindling in the coat.<ref name=\"ENCI profile\">[http://www.enci.it/en/breeds/standard.php?id=343 Cane Corso Standard] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111102125/http://www.enci.it/en/breeds/standard.php?id=343 |date=2009-01-11 }} of [[Ente Nazionale della Cinofilia Italiana]] (ENCI)</ref>\n\nCane Corso appear in two basic coat colours: black and fawn. This is further modified by genetic pigment [[Dilution gene|dilution]] to create \"blue\" (grey, from black) and frumentino or formentino (from fawn, where the mask is blue/grey) colours. [[Brindle|Brindling]] of varying intensity is common on both basic coat colours as well, creating Tigrato (black brindle), and Grigio Tigrato (blue brindle).  White markings are common on the chest, tips of toes, the chin, and the bridge of the nose.\n\nA 2017 study of 232 Cane Corso dogs across 25 countries found an average life span of 9.3 years, varying with different coat colours. The longest living were black brindle dogs (10.3 years) followed by brindle dogs (10.1 years), grey brindle dogs (9.8 years), fawn dogs (9.0 years), black dogs (9.0 years), grey dogs (9.0 years) and other colour dogs (8.1 years).<ref>{{citation |journal=Open Veterinary Journal |title=Longevity of Cane Corso Italiano dog breed and its relationship with hair colour |last=Korec |first=Ev\u017een |year=2017 |volume=7 |number=2 |pp=170\u2013173 |url=http://www.openveterinaryjournal.com/2017/Volume%207%20No%202/OVJ-2017-02-036%20E.%20Korec%20et%20al.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThese dogs are docile and affectionate to their owners, loving with children and family, and easily trained. They are an unequalled protector of the owners and their property.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.akc.org/pdf/breeds/standards/CaneCorso.pdf|title=AKC Official Standard of the Cane Corso|publisher=|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref>\nThey can also be very aggressive toward strangers and difficult to handle from a veterinary standpoint.\n\nThe average litter size of Cane Corso is 4 to 6 puppies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dogbreedinfo.com/canecorsoitaliano.htm|title=Cane Corso Italiano Dog Breed Information and Pictures|website=www.dogbreedinfo.com|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Cane Corso is a descendant of the old Roman [[molosser]].<ref name=\"FCI\"/> Its name derives from ''cane da corso'', an old term for those [[catch dog]]s used in rural activities for cattle and swine, as distinct from ''cane da camera'' which indicates the catch dog kept as a bodyguard. In the recent past, its distribution was limited to some regions of Southern Italy, especially in [[Basilicata]], [[Campania]], and [[Apulia]].<ref name=\"ENCI profile\" />\n\nCane Corso were used to guard property, livestock, and families, and some continue to be used for this purpose today. Historically it has also been used by night watchmen, keepers, [[Carting|carters]] and [[Droving|drovers]].\n\nAs life changed in the southern Italian rural farms in the 20th century, the Corso began to become rare.  A group of enthusiasts began recovery activities designed to bring the dog back from near extinction in the late 1970s.  By 1994, the breed was fully accepted by the Italian Kennel Club ([[Italian Kennel Club|ENCI]]) as the 14th Italian breed of dog.  The [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Cynologique Internationale|FCI]] provisionally accepted the Corso in 1997, and ten years later was fully recognised internationally.  In the US, the [[American Kennel Club]] first recognized the Cane Corso in 2010.<ref name=\"Get to Know the Cane Corso\"/> The popularity of the breed continues to grow, ranking in 40th place in the United States in 2016, a jump from 50th place in 2013 and 60th in 2012 <ref>[http://www.akc.org/news/the-most-popular-dog-breeds-in-america/ \"AKC Dog Registration Statistics\"], ''The American Kennel Club'', accessed 20 May 2014</ref> Today the breed is used as a guardian, protection, tracking and police dog.<ref name=UKC/>\n\n\n\n<gallery perrow=\"4\" widths=\"168px\" heights=\"168px\">\nFile:Cane corso temi 2 1024x768x24.png|Cane Corso with uncropped ears.\nFile:CaneCorso.jpg|Cane Corso, blue coat, cropped ears\nFile:Viggo-Ears-n-Tail.png|Cane Corso with ears and tail, brown/brindle coat\nFile:1 Cyrano 63b.JPG|thumb|Formentino Cane Corso puppy \n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- DO NOT ADD PRIVATE BREEDERS OR ADVERTISING; IT WILL BE REMOVED -->\n<!--Editors: breed registry, club, rescue, and kennel information links are placed on DMOZ, not here-->{{Commons category|Cane Corso}}\n* {{dmoz|Recreation/Pets/Dogs/Breeds/Molosser_Group/Cane_Corso/|Cane Corso}}\n{{Italian dogs}}\n{{Mastiffs}}\n[[Category:FCI breeds]]\n